I/O Redirection means sending the output or error of a command to a file instead of the screen.
# > (Redirect output and overwrite)
    Meaning: Send the output to a file (if the file exists, it will be erased).
    Example: echo "Hello" > file.txt

# >> (Redirect output and append)
    Meaning: Add the output to the end of the file (don't erase existing content).
    Example: echo "Another line" >> file.txt

# 2> (Redirect error output)
    Meaning: Send error messages to a file.
    Example: ls not_a_file 2> error.t
